Even then racial discrimination was legal. In the 1930s, a man was denied service at a Montreal tavern because he was Black. The Supreme Court of Canada allowed it.
Slavery wasn’t abolished in British North American until 1834. That was only a few decades before the Emancipation Proclamation in the States.
By 1800, there were more slaves in the Maritimes than there were in any place in British North America — about 2000.
The first slave sold in what was to become Canada?  It was a 7 year-old child. He was sold by British traders to a French clerk. A child.

data.text: We poached @chefcraigflinn again this year for another egg-cellent workshop that had everyone feeling sunnyside. Omelette you finish that bite before you tell us how good it was 😉🥚 https://t.co/RjwsHvGeZa
We had so many amazing @TasteofNS local businesses at our opening gala this year! Can you even pick a favourite? https://t.co/PEwooKxJGw
RT @TasteCanada: THANK YOU to the #TasteCanada Ambassadors! Your advocation for the awards truly demonstrated our theme of “One Canada. One…

There is no Devour! without you, our guests, and we were so happy to welcome you back to our seats for a little more of what we live for, food and film! 

Note: this photo was taken prior to the COVID-19 pandemic. https://t.co/YmBh5uRu8N

Now THIS is how you Devour! @ Home! @EpicAimeeSilver was extra prepared to stream her @BishopsCellar wine tasting at home. Did you Devour! from home this year? Post your at-home set-ups and tag us! https://t.co/4jKJ2AmgSo

For their vision, leadership, and stalwart community support, thank you to Chef Michael Howell and Lia Rinaldo, our Executive and Managing Directors.   

Thank you. Here’s to an endless buffet marathon of Devour! Fests! https://t.co/l66x1PAHqj

Every day we are privileged to live in the legacy of our veterans.

They shall grow not old, as we that are left grow old:
Age shall not weary them, nor the years condemn.
At the going down of the sun and in the morning
We will remember them.

Excerpt of For the Fallen, L. Binyon https://t.co/dFbrrBo73J

They say many hands make light work, and if that were true, Devour!’s workload would be as light as a feather. But the truth is, this festival continues to be a success because of the heavy lifting each of you do every year. Thank you for your continued dedication. https://t.co/F4WFyCrmWU

While Devour!-goers are taking in the sights and sounds (and flavours!) of the festival, it’s our staff who are shoveling the coal that keeps this train rolling. The accolades of Devour! are a direct reflection of the time, dedication, and perseverance of our staff.  
#DevourFest https://t.co/r6dT5764ra

After 40+ festivals and 11 awards (most recently winning the Jury Award at Berkshire IFF) FISH & MEN, which screened at Devour! 9.5, has been released to VOD and DVD through Virgil Films. It is available to rent or buy on all major digital platforms here https://t.co/GaLr2h0JKy https://t.co/SOLKNTi1oP

Congratulations to Tomson Highway who was recently announced as the Hilary Weston Writers’ Trust Prize winner for Nonfiction for his book, Permanent Astonishment: A Memoir. 

You can purchase Tomson’s book in our Devour! Shop at https://t.co/TiMil1cyJC 

#DevourFest #Devour2021 https://t.co/yBhIwkVaTL

Our sponsor’s contributions not only support the food film festival we all love, but the success of an entire community in a typical down season. A huge round of applause to them for their continued support👏👏👏 

See this year’s sponsors here: https://t.co/g5BMlUwgMb https://t.co/jan2pwbvY5

We were very excited to have the Valley Regional Hospital Foundation as a partnering sponsor for the Indigenous Cooking Master Classes for Youth as well as the The RBC Big Picture Program: School Gardens.  @VRHFoundation 
 #DevourFest #Devour2021 #CommunityIsOurFoundation https://t.co/lyMhq7gDQU

Garrett Gloade, Mill Brook First Nation. Curation and management of Mi’kmaq Mawi'omi (pow wow) at Devour! Opening Ceremonies.

Stéphane Levac, Ojibwa, Chef at Oak Island Resort. Working alongside our Culinary Coordinator, Jason Lynch, and the Devour! Team.
Joseph Shawana, Odawa, Three Fires Confederacy. Founder & Chair of Indigenous Culinary of Associated Nations. Indigenous culinary supervisor. Oversight and curation of all food across the event.
•Zabrina Whitman, Glooscap First Nation. Advisory Panel, Indigenous liaisons, and creative contributor.

Devour! 2021 would not be possible without the guidance, input, and support of our Indigenous Partners: 
•Chief Sidney Peters, Glooscap First Nation. Elder guidance, support and opening prayer.

We, very literally, could not have done this without the support of our Indigenous Advisors and Organizers. Your leadership, your willingness to share your culture, your knowledge and your skills transformed Devour! this year into a Global Indigenous experience. https://t.co/61iiN78UQ7

🎥AND CUT!🎥 That’s a wrap for Devour! Fest 2021, celebrating Global Indigenous Cinema & Cuisine. We hope to see everyone again at the 12th edition of Devour!, slated for October Oct 24-30, 2022 🎥🍽
